headline: Target, Lowe's, TJX earnings, July FOMC minutes: What to Watch
summary: Here's what investors are watching on Wednesday, August 20. On the earnings front, retailers continue to release results with TJX (TJX), Lowe's (LOW), and Target (TGT) set to release their quarterly reports. Investors will get additional commentary from Federal Reserve officials, with Fed Governor Christopher Waller and Atlanta Fed president Raphael Bostic set to deliver remarks. The minutes from the July FOMC meeting are also set to be released. To watch more expert insights and analysis on the latest market action, check out more Market Domination Overtime.

headline: Trading Day: Tech it down a notch
summary: Wall Street slumped on Tuesday, dragged down by weakness in some of the big tech companies that have led the charge to new highs this year, as investors hunker down ahead of a keynote speech by Fed Chair Jerome Powell later this week.  In my column today I look at the cagey dance between Donald Trump and Wall Street - the market knows it has the power to rein in some of the president's policy excesses, but isn't wielding it.  Trump says Putin may not want to make a deal on Ukraine  2.

headline: Why TJX could be the 'surprise' retail winner this earnings season
summary: TJX (TJX) could surprise to the upside as it benefits from excess department store inventory, says B. Riley Wealth chief market strategist Art Hogan. Hogan joins Market Domination to discuss how value-focused retailers are navigating tariffs and what to watch for in consumer spending. To watch more expert insights and analysis on the latest market action, check out more Market Domination.

headline: Stock Futures Stall With Retail Earnings in Focus. Markets Brace for Signs of Slowdown.
summary: Stock futures were broadly flat before the market opened on Tuesday ahead of a raft of earnings from big-name retailers.  Home Depot, the nationwide chain for do-it-yourself renovators, reports results from the latest quarter before the exchange starts trading today.  Mass market retailers Target and TJX are up on Wednesday.
